**Q:** why do we do spearman and not pearson for the correlation? we didnt really cover that distinction in class

**A:** Pearson correlation assumes a roughly linear relationship and works best when both variables are normally distributed. Your view counts are heavily right-skewed (a few videos have 100M views, most have 100K), so the distribution assumption is violated. Spearman uses the ranks of the values instead of the raw values, so it handles that skew without requiring transformation. It is more appropriate for social media data.

