**Q:** but titles like "SHOCKING: iPhone Battery EXPLODES" are getting negative scores around -0.4 even though these are viral clickbait titles. shouldnt those be scoring as high arousal?

**A:** VADER is working correctly. It identifies words like "explodes" and "shocking" as negative-valence words and scores them accordingly. The issue is a conceptual one: VADER measures semantic sentiment (does this text express negative emotion?) not psychological impact on the reader. YouTube creators use negative-emotion words to create urgency and capture attention, not to express genuine negativity about the topic. VADER has no way to distinguish between a bad review and a clickbait title using the same words. This is actually an interesting limitation to discuss in your paper.

