**Q:** i want to compare view counts across my three sentiment groups (positive, neutral, negative). my instinct was to run three t-tests. is that right?

**A:** Three separate t-tests would inflate your false positive rate. Each test has a 5% chance of false positives at alpha=0.05, but running three tests compounds that error. Use a one-way ANOVA instead, which tests whether any of the three groups differ simultaneously. If ANOVA is significant, you can then run post-hoc pairwise comparisons with a Tukey correction, which adjusts for multiple comparisons.

---

**Q:** what is a Tukey test and why do i need it after ANOVA? we didn't cover this in class

**A:** ANOVA tells you that at least one pair of groups differs but not which pair. Tukey's Honest Significant Difference test does all pairwise comparisons (positive vs neutral, positive vs negative, neutral vs negative) while controlling the overall false positive rate. Without it, you'd have to run three t-tests and inflate your error rate. With Tukey, you can say specifically "neutral titles outperform negative titles (p < 0.01) but do not significantly differ from positive titles (p = 0.12)."

