**Q:** wait what is a confidence interval and how is it different from a p-value? i keep seeing both and im confused about which one i should report

**A:** A p-value tells you the probability of seeing a result this extreme if the true effect were zero. It is a binary signal about statistical significance. A confidence interval tells you the plausible range of the true effect size. A 95% confidence interval means: if you repeated this study many times, 95% of the intervals you computed would contain the true value. Confidence intervals are more informative because they show both the direction and the uncertainty around your estimate. Best practice is to report both.

